• Initiate with a Buy and a DKr158 TP (+18.6% ETR) — We believe that GN can deliver a FY14-17E sales CAGR of 9.8% and an EPS CAGR of 19.7%, supported by a DKr1bn (>4%) annual share buyback. GN’s wireless connectivity advantage in hearing aids (made for iPhone, etc) should last until 2016-17 in our view, while the increasing uptake of Unified Communications (UC) technology should accelerate growth and margin for its headset business, Netcom.
  • Our 2017E Netcom (headset) EBITA is 14% ahead of consensus — We believe GN could gain further share in the UC headset market in 2015-16 due to a recent large contract win, driving a >25% UC sales CAGR and accelerating Netcom’s organic growth from 10% in 2014E to 14% in 2016E vs 12% consensus. Given our est. that UC is accretive to Netcom’s margin and our expectation of a turnaround in the music-product margin following a portfolio optimization in 1H14, we forecast a turnaround in Netcom’s EBITA margin from 17.8% in 2014E to 20.3% in 2017E (150bp ahead of cons. At 18.8%).
  • Cautious on 1H15 margin — While we are positive on the mid-term outlook for GN, we would caution that the company could continue to face margin headwinds from US$ strength in 1H15 (due to having hedged 1-yr fwd), before this reverses from 2H15. Further to this there could be an ongoing headwind from a narrowing gap between R&D capitalisation and amortisation but we feel this is now better understood than with Sonova given it was flagged by the CFO on the 3Q call.
  • PEG 0.85x, recent de-rating largely factors in near-term risks — GN is trading on 17x our 2016E adj. EPS, which is <1% above consensus, for an estimated 2014E-17E adj. EPS CAGR of 19.7% (PEG 0.85x) vs 13% for the sector (PEG 1.4x). This is a 7% discount to the sector despite GN’s superior earnings growth on our forecasts and we therefore believe GN’s recent de-rating largely factors-in near-term risks to margin and GN’s Costco Kirkland Signature contract.
